{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.03,0.07,0.6,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3591"},{"type":"tags","id":"4913"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset of lightheadedness and diaphoresis. She suffers an unconscious collapse in the waiting room and is transferred to the resuscitation bay. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Initial assessment reveals likely hypoglycaemia, with a random blood glucose level of 1.3 mmol/L (4.0-11.1) on a glucometer. Given her impaired conscious state, she is administered glucagon intramuscularly whilst intravenous access is obtained. Her blood glucose level improves to 7.8 mmol/L within minutes, and she soon regains consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther history reveals no previous diagnosis of diabetes in herself or immediate family. She lives with a roommate who has type 1 diabetes mellitus. Review of her electronic medical record reveals multiple similar presentations with unexplained hypoglycaemic episodes at other hospitals. Her roommate, who is present, discretely expresses concern that her insulin pens have gone missing at home on several occasions. Blood samples are taken at the time of the hypoglycaemic episode for further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of laboratory results would be most consistent with this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood glucose low, plasma insulin high, C-peptide high","Blood glucose high, plasma insulin low, C-peptide low","Blood glucose low, plasma insulin low, C-peptide low","Blood glucose low, plasma insulin high, C-peptide low","Blood glucose high, plasma insulin high, C-peptide high"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with Whipple\u0027s triad for hypoglycaemia: low blood glucose, symptoms of hypoglycaemia, and resolution of symptoms with glucose administration. Given the circumstances of this patient\u0027s presentation, including recurrent unexplained hypoglycaemic episodes and potential access to insulin, factitious hypoglycaemia due to exogenous insulin administration is highly likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most consistent set of laboratory results would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood glucose low, plasma insulin high, C-peptide low\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination is diagnostic of exogenous insulin administration. The low blood glucose confirms hypoglycaemia. The high plasma insulin level during a hypoglycaemic event is abnormal and indicates hyperinsulinaemia. However, the low C-peptide level is crucial in differentiating exogenous from endogenous sources of insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood glucose low, plasma insulin high, C-peptide high\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest endogenous hyperinsulinaemia, as seen in conditions like insulinoma. In this case, both insulin and C-peptide would be elevated as they are produced in equimolar amounts by pancreatic beta cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood glucose high, plasma insulin low, C-peptide low\u003C/strong\u003E is not consistent with the clinical presentation of hypoglycaemia. This pattern might be seen in type 1 diabetes with inadequate insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood glucose low, plasma insulin low, C-peptide low\u003C/strong\u003E could indicate hypoglycaemia due to non-insulin mediated causes, such as liver failure or adrenal insufficiency, which is not consistent with the clinical suspicion in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood glucose high, plasma insulin high, C-peptide high\u003C/strong\u003E is not consistent with hypoglycaemia and might be seen in insulin-resistant states like type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of suspected factitious hypoglycaemia, it\u0027s important to obtain blood samples during the hypoglycaemic episode. The combination of low blood glucose, high plasma insulin, and low C-peptide is diagnostic of exogenous insulin administration. This patient likely requires psychiatric evaluation given the potential for self-harm associated with this behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of symptomatic hypoglycaemia meeting the criteria of Whipple\u0027s triad are due to excessive exogenous insulin.","The combination of low blood glucose, high plasma insulin, and low C-peptide levels is diagnostic of exogenous insulin administration.","Factitious hypoglycaemia should be considered in patients with recurrent unexplained hypoglycaemic episodes, especially if they have access to insulin."],"references":["Cryer PE et al, 2009. \u0027Evaluation and Management of Adult Hypoglycaemic Disorders: An Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline\u0027 in Journal of Clinical Endocrinology and Metabolism\u0027, vol 94, pp 709-728, https://academic.oup.com/jcem/article/94/3/709/2596247."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87245"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T12:32:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T12:32:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1339"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"typ